<title>
Kinome-wide RNAi screen implicates at least 5 host hepatocyte kinases in Plasmodium sporozoite infection.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
lthough malaria has long been a devastating killer for the most vulnerable populations in countries of sub-aharan frica and other developing nations, our understanding of the early host-parasite interactions underlying this infectious disease remains far from complete. n fact, the first stage of a malaria infection, which occurs in the liver once the lasmodium parasite has been delivered through the bite of an infected female nopheles mosquito, is still clearly under-studied today.
nce inside the mammalian host, lasmodium sporozoites, the motile form that is delivered in the mosquito's saliva, display a marked tropism for hepatocytes, the cells that enable the remarkable replication process that will give rise to thousands of merozoites from each invading parasite (reviewed in [1]). s a first step towards infection, several hepatocytes are transiently traversed by the sporozoite before one cell is productively invaded, leading to the formation of a parasitophorous vacuole [2]. ithin this cytosolic vacuole, the subsequent development and asexual replication of lasmodium, constituting so-called exoerythrocytic forms (s), achieve one of the fastest growth rates among all eukaryotic cells. he invaded hepatocyte eventually releases thousands of mature merozoites into the bloodstream [3], where these then invade erythrocytes, thereby initiating the so-called blood stage of infection and triggering the well-known symptoms of malaria. oth the strong tropism and obligate nature of the events that take place during liver infection suggest an essential requirement for hepatocyte-specific factors in enabling this complex lead-up to the blood stage. t is therefore of primary interest to identify and characterize the role of such host factors, as these may contribute to the design of rational interventional strategies for the development of novel prophylactic agents.
o this end, we have used a cultured cell-based assay to study the process of liver infection by lasmodium parasites at the cellular and molecular level. sing human uh7 hepatoma cells and sporozoites of the rodent parasite . berghei freshly isolated from infected nopheles mosquitoes, we have established a high throughput assay system (igure 1) that, combined with high content readouts using automated microscopy, and quantitative - (q. RT-PCR), can be used for RNA interference (RNAi) and/or drug screening experiments. Intracellular phosphorylation and dephosphorylation events are enzymatically catalysed by kinases and phosphatases, respectively, and constitute the most important signalling mechanisms known in eukaryotic cells [4]. The phosphorylation state of a protein can determine its activity and, thereby, regulate the pathway(s) in which it is involved. Thus, the present study probed the potential role of key components of host hepatocyte signal transduction pathways, focusing on kinases as key regulators for a wide range of cellular functions.
10.1371/journal.ppat.1000201.g001Figure 1RNA interference screen strategy for identification of host factors affecting Plasmodium infection.(A) Experimental design of a high-throughput RNAi screen to identify host genes that influence Plasmodium sporozoite infection of host cells. (B) Validation of siRNA-mediated knock-down in Huh7 cells. Knock-down efficiency of 53 genes was evaluated by qRT-PCR following Huh7 cell transfection with 3 independent siRNAs per targeted gene.
