<sections.2>
Discussion
he approach described here constitutes, to our knowledge, the first report of a genome-scale i screen for key host factors for infection of human cells by a parasite. lasmodium sporozoite infection in vitro assays are fraught with specific biological variability issues that enhance the difficulties inherent to any high-throughput i screening assay. hus, in order to minimize the chance of excluding false negative and identifying false positive results, we have devised a multi-step strategy employing increasingly stringent selection criteria throughout the screen. evertheless, we cannot definitively rule out the possibility of, in this process, having discarded candidates that may indeed play a role during infection, but which did not β€�surviveβ€� the criteria employed throughout the three stages of selection. or this reason, we encourage the reader to consult able 1, where details of the screening process are presented and potentially relevant genes can be identified.
ur systematic analysis of the human kinome in the context of the liver stage of malaria infection has directly implicated at least five host kinases in this process: , 1, 2, 35 and ¶. y doing so through direct functional tests for each of the genes assayed, this dataset establishes clear causal roles in the processes examined and reveals novel key host molecules in these pathways that significantly affect lasmodium's success in infecting hepatocytes.
mong our top hits, the  gene, which encodes the hepatocyte growth factor () receptor, is the only one to have been previously shown to influence lasmodium infection of hepatocytes [24],[25], an effect that has been proposed to occur through inhibition of apoptosis [25]. t has been demonstrated that transfection of hepatoma cells with a dominant-negative form of  leads to a reduction in lasmodium infection while transfection with a constitutively active form results in an infection increase [24]. hus, the emergence of  as one of our top hits whose knock-down consistently led to a decrease in infection represents a validation of the screening methodology used here, and strengthens the predictive value of the other hits. mong those, both 2 and 1 are serine/threonine kinases that have been implicated in osmotic control through the regulation of a+ and + transport channels [26]β€“[29]. own-modulation of both of these osmotic and oxidative stress-responsive proteins also led to a reduced infection in the present screen. lthough their role in lasmodium infection remains unclear, the present data may be highlighting the importance of maintaining an optimal osmotic balance in the host cell to permit successful infection. n addition, it has recently been shown that exposure of sporozoites to the intracellular + concentration enhances sporozoite infectivity [30]. hether or not 2 or 1 act on infection through the control of + concentration will require further investigation. oncerning 35, it is known to interact with -36, a - protein, and re-localize from the nucleus to actin stress fibres [31]. his has led to the suggestion that 35 may act as a regulator of the actin-myosin cytoskeleton in non-muscle cells [31]. ndeed, there are indications that the reorganization of the host cell actin cytoskeleton may be important for lasmodium infection [24]. hus, it is appealing to consider the hypothesis that recruitment of 35 may influence lasmodium infection by playing a role in this process.
inally, the gene which we have characterized in most detail here, ¶, is part of the large family of s that has been implicated in numerous cellular processes.  isotypes include 10β€“15 members, divided into 4 groups [10],[16]. ne of these groups, known as the atypical s (a. PKCs) [11], comprises the PKCΞ¶ [12] and PKCΞ»/ΞΉ (PKCiota/lambda) [13] isoforms. The aPKCs have been implicated in numerous processes, including cell growth and survival, regulation of NF-ΞΊB activation and polarity (reviewed in [11],[14],[15]). In the present study, loss of PKCΞ¶ function both in vitro and in vivo, whether by RNAi silencing or by pseudo-substrate inhibition, led to decreased infection rates. This unequivocally establishes a key role of PKCΞ¶ in host liver malarial infection, thereby, giving confidence that the other genes identified in the RNAi screen also play a relevant role during infection. Furthermore, as we gain additional understanding of the pathway defined by PKCΞ¶ in this context, its potential biomedical value may develop not merely as one, but rather also as the founding member in an entirely novel class of anti-malarial drug target. In addition, our data reveals a role for PKCΞ¶ signaling in host cell invasion by Plasmodium sporozoites. To our knowledge, this is the first host cell signaling molecule to be identified as an important player in Plasmodium invasion and paves the way to a better understanding of this essential host-Plasmodium interaction in the establishment of a malaria infection.
The interaction of a pathogen with its host cell activates intracellular signaling cascades that regulate innate immune responses and govern the outcome of infection (see [32] for a recent review on this topic). These signaling pathways may also be exploited by the pathogen to its own benefit as was recently suggested for the interaction of hepatitis C virus, another major liver pathogen, with its target cells [33]. While our present study does not demonstrate any active exploitation or modulation of host signal transduction pathways by Plasmodium, it does reveal novel key host molecules in these pathways that significantly affect the parasite's success in infecting hepatocytes. Our efforts are thus starting to yield crucial molecular details needed to build a coherent picture of the key cellular events taking place during the liver phase of malaria infection.
Altogether, these results contribute toward a better understanding of host-pathogen interactions, which may help in accelerating the rational design of prophylactic, therapeutic and/or diagnostic strategies aimed to control malaria.
